class StockPrice {
public:
    StockPrice() {

    }

    void update(int timestamp, int price) {
        prices[timestamp] = price;
        max_prices.clear();
        min_prices.clear();
    }

    int current() {
        auto it = prices.rbegin();
        return it->second;
    }

    int maximum() {
        if (max_prices.empty()) {
            for (auto& pair : prices) {
                max_prices.insert(pair.second);
            }
        }
        return *max_prices.rbegin();
    }

    int minimum() {
        if (min_prices.empty()) {
            for (auto& pair : prices) {
                min_prices.insert(pair.second);
            }
        }
        return *min_prices.begin();
    }
private:
    std::map<int, int> prices;
    std::set<int> max_prices;
    std::set<int> min_prices;
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: 
- update: O(log N) 
- current: O(1) 
- maximum: O(N) 
- minimum: O(N) 
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: MEDIUM
explanation: The provided solution efficiently handles stock price updates and queries. It utilizes a map to store timestamps and their corresponding prices, allowing for O(log N) updates. The current price is retrieved in O(1) time by simply accessing the most recent entry in the map. Maximum and minimum prices are maintained using sets, which are populated on their first query; subsequent queries are O(1). However, initial population of these sets can take O(N) time. Overall, this approach balances efficiency with acceptable space usage.

